olitical conservatism. He argues that Americanism was a complex, even contradictory, language of nationalism that lent itself to a wide variety of ideological constructions in the years between World War I and the onset of the Cold War. Using the rich and textured material left behind by New England's most powerful textile union--the Independent Textile Union of Woonsocket, Rhode Island--Gerstle uncovers for the first time a more varied and more radical working-class discourse.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aTextile industryzRhode IslandzWoonsocketxHistoryy20th century. 0aTextile workerszRhode IslandzWoonsocketxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh  aAlsace spinning mill.  aAmalgamated Clothing Workers.  aAmerican Legion.  aAmericanization campaigns.  aArmenian workers.  aBlackstone Cotton local.  aBonin Spinning mill.  aBouvier, Joseph.  aCanzano, Victor.  aCardijn, Cardinal.  aCatholic Church.  aChristian Family Movement.  aCourtemanche, Jude.  aDaignault, Elphège.  aDesurmont spinning mill.  aDivini Redemptoris.  aEnglish immigrants.  aFalls Yarn mill.  aFranco-American identity.  aFrench Worsted mill.  aGoval, Charles.  aGuerin Mills-Rosemont.  aHowe, Irving.  aITU radicals.  aIndependent Club.  aIndustrial pluralism.  aJews.  aJoyland Ballroom.  aKeynesianism.  aLawton Spinning.  aNational War Labor Board.  aPeck Law.  aPilgrims.  aPortuguese workers.  aProvidence Journal.  aQuebec.  aanticommunism.  aarbitration.  abenefits.  acorporatism, Catholic.  adues collection.  aethnic corporatists.  aethnic lodges.  aideological independence.  ajob security.  akinship networks.  aliberalism.  amanagement prerogatives.  amillowners.  amulespinners.  anativism.  aopen-books 